<div id="review_3021861539" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3021861539" />
    <a title="Donna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2100090-donna"><img alt="Donna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1622818767p2/2100090.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3021861539?book_show_action=true">Jan 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Donna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Donna" href="/user/show/2100090-donna">Donna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3021861539" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8186285800364038102">4.5 stars<br/><br/>In the late 1980s, there was a period of reform and democracy movements in China that culminated in violence on June 4, 1989, when the Chinese government unleashed the PLA on its own people in Beijing&apos;s Tiananmen Square. Most Westerners recognize the iconic photo of &quot;Tank Man&quot; - a lone man facing down four tanks in the recently emptied square a day later. But in China, a deliberate, ruthless, and systematic subversion of this event has successfully erased it from the collective memory o</span>
  <span id="freeText8186285800364038102" style="display:none">4.5 stars<br /><br />In the late 1980s, there was a period of reform and democracy movements in China that culminated in violence on June 4, 1989, when the Chinese government unleashed the PLA on its own people in Beijing's Tiananmen Square. Most Westerners recognize the iconic photo of "Tank Man" - a lone man facing down four tanks in the recently emptied square a day later. But in China, a deliberate, ruthless, and systematic subversion of this event has successfully erased it from the collective memory of the Chinese people. In fact, when shown a picture of Tank Man to 100 university students in Beijing, the author found only 15 who could correctly identify it. And of those who did, most dismissed it as propaganda or fake news. <br /><br />In this fascinating and chilling piece of historical reportage, Louisa Lim shares the stories of people who participated in or were effected by the events surrounding Tiananmen. These include a sensitive young soldier who was handed a camera to record the scene, a mother whose young son was killed and who has refused to remain silent, and an aging official with conflicted feelings about his participation. All of the stories are riveting, heartbreaking, and unforgettable.<br /><br />Lim also recounts a similar and little known violent episode at Tianfu Square in the city of Chengdu. She reflects on China's current political and economical state and the emergent student-led demonstrations in Hong Kong. <br /><br />My daughter's college best friend has lived in Beijing as an expat for the past 15 or so years and describes this as her most recommended book on China. Highly recommended by me as well. <br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8186285800364038102" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


