<div id="review_1850368636" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1850368636" />
    <a title="Sonya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32463550-sonya"><img alt="Sonya" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1548174042p2/32463550.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1850368636?book_show_action=true">Jul 12, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sonya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sonya" href="/user/show/32463550-sonya">Sonya</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1850368636" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9642351432591153388">This book is haunting. Lim writes extraordinarily compellingly yet her words take patience to read, because the historical accounts she tells holds her reader to reading every word -- demanding that her readers know the stories that have otherwise been buried and rewritten by China. For me personally, I really wanted to keep reading while also finding a lot of the book hard to swallow because of the tragedy and how hope was gained and lost over and over again. I found the chapter about the Tiana</span>
  <span id="freeText9642351432591153388" style="display:none">This book is haunting. Lim writes extraordinarily compellingly yet her words take patience to read, because the historical accounts she tells holds her reader to reading every word -- demanding that her readers know the stories that have otherwise been buried and rewritten by China. For me personally, I really wanted to keep reading while also finding a lot of the book hard to swallow because of the tragedy and how hope was gained and lost over and over again. I found the chapter about the Tiananmen Mothers was particularly heartbreaking. <br /><br />Lim is extraordinarily critical of the way the Chinese government has handled the politics of memory and she builds a very compelling and moving case for her critique. At the same time, it almost feels wrong to call her work a critique, because its power comes from how it bears witnesses to the violence - both in terms of physical violence and the violence of suppressing historical truth for almost 30 years. It is a daringly persistent pursuit of historical truth done by tracing both individual trauma and resilience and the top-down arc of Chinese politics. It's hard to do justice to this book in a short review, but I would wholeheartedly recommend this book to anyone interested in Chinese politics, social movements, and the politics of memory.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9642351432591153388" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


