  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3043052867" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3043052867" />
    <a title="Rob Hocking" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59423708-rob-hocking"><img alt="Rob Hocking" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1473317262p2/59423708.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3043052867?book_show_action=true">Nov 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rob Hocking" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rob Hocking" href="/user/show/59423708-rob-hocking">Rob Hocking</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3043052867" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9255184236019607529">This book mostly consists of separate stories of seven individuals who lived through or were affected by Tiananmen. She has a pretty good mix of interviewees - not only students but also a soldier and a government official, as well as the mom of a student who died. However, obviously the fact that the solider and official she found were willing to talk to her in the first place means that we aren&apos;t getting the views representative of the average soldier/official.<br/><br/>Besides these seven stories, the </span>
  <span id="freeText9255184236019607529" style="display:none">This book mostly consists of separate stories of seven individuals who lived through or were affected by Tiananmen. She has a pretty good mix of interviewees - not only students but also a soldier and a government official, as well as the mom of a student who died. However, obviously the fact that the solider and official she found were willing to talk to her in the first place means that we aren't getting the views representative of the average soldier/official.<br /><br />Besides these seven stories, the author also tells the story of separate protests happening in Chengdu at the same time. This story doesn't follow any specific individual and instead is a mix of the various bits of information she was able to glean from different sources. Her purpose in telling this story is to illustrate that Tiananmen was actually part of a larger movement in cities all over China - the movement in Beijing is just the most famous. Similarly, the Tiananmen massacre was actually just one of many massacres that occurred in the country when the movement was crushed.<br /><br />Besides the stories of 1989, the book also goes into great lengths in describing the persecution of individuals in China - up to the present day - who have spoken out about it. In that sense, I think that even if you have no interest in Tiananmen, this book is an excellent place to start if you want to understand the extent to which freedom of speech does not exist in present-day China. One example that stands out in my memory:<br /><br />The dissident Zhu Yufu was given a 7-year prison sentence for writing a poem that included the words<br /><br />It's time, Chinese people!<br />The square belongs to everyone.<br />Your feet are your own.<br />It's time to use your feet and head to the square to make your choice.<br /><br />This poem was never published, rather it was sent to a friend over Skype.<br /><br />Now, of course, we are missing a lot of context. What did the rest of the poem say? Did Zhu Yufu have an otherwise clean record, besides writing this poem? Finally - the one I'm most interested to know - how did the government even find out about the poem, if it was sent over Skype? Unfortunately, the book doesn't answer any of these questions. <br /><br />Another example has to do with mainland supporters of the 2014 Umbrella movement in Hong Kong:<br /><br />Meanwhile, fear of a contagion effect from the Umbrella movement sweeping across the border had set off a whole new wave of repression. More than a hundred mainland supporters of the Hong Kong protests were detained. The reasons listed by one overseas human rights group constitute a catalogue of paranoia: for posting a message of solidarity with the Occupy Central participants; for attempts to go to Hong Kong to show solidarity; for posting a picture of himself with a shaved head, holding an umbrella, and sticking up his middle finger.<br /><br />Again, we're missing a lot of context, which is unfortunate. <br /><br />Final example (this is concerning a piece of performance art):<br /><br />At the end of April, he [the artist] had invited a handful of friends - including foreign journalists - to an art installation. As the guests sat in the pitch black, a four-year-old girl dressed in white shone a flashlight, illuminating walls painted with dates beginning in 1989 and ending with 2014. When the lights came on, Chen [the artist] whitewashed the walls. "The history is like a blank," he told spectators, "It has been wiped out." For that act, he was detained for more than five weeks.<br /><br />I think it's illustrative to stop for a moment and compare this with the approach to "embarrassing history" taken in Taiwan. I'm going to quote directly from another thing I wrote, regarding a question I was asked by two of my mainland friends on the difference between Taiwan and Mainland China:<br /><br />"Do you know what the "White Terror" period in Taiwan is? You don't? Ok, this is what it is: In 1945, the Nationalist government of China is suddenly given control of Taiwan, which for the past 50 years has been a colony of Japan. Because it's been a colony of Japan, Taiwan is far more advanced at that time than the mainland. This would have been true even had there not been a war - however, in addition, mainland China has been devastated by the war with Japan. So you have this situation where the Nationalists have just been given control of this island which is far, far more wealthy than any of their territory on the mainland. At the same time, because the Taiwanese have been Japanese subjects for 50 years, the Nationalists don't see them as real Chinese. Now, at the same time as this is happening the Nationalists are also fighting an increasingly desperate civil war with the communists on the mainland. And so there is this temptation: "These Taiwanese aren't really Chinese anyways - they're effectively Japanese. That makes it ok for us to loot Taiwan in order to fund the civil war". So this is exactly what happens, and not surprisingly, it doesn't go over very well. By 1947 you have large scale revolts by the Taiwanese. These are brutally suppressed by the Nationalists, with something like 40,000 Taiwanese either being killed or sent to prison. <br /><br />Now, for a long time, all of this was covered up, but now it's out in the open. There is a museum in Taipei dedicated to the "White Terror". Before coming here, I went to visit that museum. While I was there, I met a man who had been falsely accused and imprisoned for 10 years during the White Terror. He told me about how he was accused of setting off a bomb in Tainan, how when the real culprit was caught, rather than being set free he was tortured and made to sign a confession for a different, made-up crime. He told me about how he thinks that even today, the Nationalist Party in Taiwan is still doing things like this.<br /><br />After I went home, I looked this man up on the internet. I found, among other things, a 30-minute documentary on YouTube telling his story: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LN5if-0wMHc">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LN5if...</a><br /><br />What does this have to do with the difference between Taiwan and China? Number one: this museum exists. Number two: This man is not in jail. Number three: His online videos have not been deleted. Number four: a VPN is not required to view his videos, as the internet has not been blocked." </span>
  <a data-text-id="9255184236019607529" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


