  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3959171094" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3959171094" />
    <a title="Weiling" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16508552-weiling"><img alt="Weiling" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1600401871p2/16508552.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3959171094?book_show_action=true">Apr 23, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Weiling" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Weiling" href="/user/show/16508552-weiling">Weiling</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16508552-weiling?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16508552-weiling?shelf=china">china</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3959171094" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15737457338465371568">It’s hard not to fall for the convenience of narration when watching from a self-righteous distance the brutality of an apparently authoritarian state in the East. What else can or is worth to be told outside the democratic/undemocratic states trope? Why bother to tell other stories and not direct all outcry to the urgency of human rights crisis? Isn’t it morally and cognitively sufficient in showing humanity to pick the suffering Chinese and the good Chinese from the bad China?<br/><br/>Fortunately, Loui</span>
  <span id="freeText15737457338465371568" style="display:none">It’s hard not to fall for the convenience of narration when watching from a self-righteous distance the brutality of an apparently authoritarian state in the East. What else can or is worth to be told outside the democratic/undemocratic states trope? Why bother to tell other stories and not direct all outcry to the urgency of human rights crisis? Isn’t it morally and cognitively sufficient in showing humanity to pick the suffering Chinese and the good Chinese from the bad China?<br /><br />Fortunately, Louisa Lim proactively dodged the alluring writing in the style of antagonism. She stayed with dilemmas and complexities while holding dictatorship accountable. A veteran turned to art to recollect his fear of killing and being killed, a student lost his promising business future as a result of his participation in the protest where he loathed the lack of strategy, a controversial student leader in exile tried to get himself arrested to return home to see his parents, aged mothers tried to live long enough to see justice done to the children they lost on the square, a high official recounted party factionalism that led to the decision of mass killing, and the overlooked bloodshed in Chengdu.<br /><br />The endeavor to forget is as prevalent as these underground efforts to remember are scattered. The extent to which blind-minded nationalism replaces memory can be quantified: the mass anti-Japan protests and TV productions, the number of death threats sent to writers of Tiananmen, the daily compensation paid to the dissident watchers etc.<br /><br />But the most shocking to me is the absence of the “China as victim of foreign power” discourse between 1947 and 1990, where, first, socialist confidence didn’t care to self-pity, and later postsocialist zeal for reform was allowed to measuredly overshadow ideological control. The post-Tiananmen patriotic education forcefully strikes the tone of victimhood to fill up the ideological vacuum left by the removal of socialist beliefs. To forget is a collective contract.<br /><br />To forget and look forward is fine until it is not, until the debt of memory, along with the interest accrued through all the years of amnesia, has to be paid.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15737457338465371568" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

